415","1440":"1440","1415":"1415","1414":"1414","1469":"1469","1489":"1489","Abt 1410":"about 1410","1367":"1367","1410":"1410","1375":"1375","1430":"1430","1407   3rd wife":"March 1407","1409":"1409","1507":"1507","1408":"1408","1405":"1405","Bradwell, Gloucestershire, England":"Bradwell-on-Sea, Essex, England, United Kingdom","Of, Bradwell, Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Twyford, Buckinghamshire, England":"Twyford, Buckinghamshire, England","Twyford, Buckinghamshire, England.":"Twyford, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Giffard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: (i) relationship name from the Continental Germanic personal name  <i>Gifard</i>. (ii) nickname, perhaps sometimes from Old French  <i>giffard</i> ‘chubby-cheeked, bloated’."],"variants":[{"name":"Jeffords","meanings":["English: variant of   Gifford  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Jefford","meanings":["English:  see  Giffard  ."]},{"name":"Guiver","meanings":["English: (i) nickname, apparently from Middle English  <i>giver</i> ‘giver, donor, bestower’. (ii) variant of   Giffard   with voicing of /f/ to /v/ and loss of final  <i>-d</i>."]},{"name":"Gafford","meanings":["English (southeastern): assimilated form of <b>Gatford</b>, a name of various origins. In Sussex and Surrey it is perhaps a variant of the habitational name <b>Catford</b> from a place so called in Somerset. <b>Gatford</b> is also from the habitational names Gateford (in Worksop, Nottinghamshire) or Gateforth (near Selby, Yorkshire), both formed with Old English <i>gāt</i> ‘goat’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’, influenced by Old Norse <i>geit</i> ‘goat’.","Probably also an altered form of German <b>Gaffert</b>: habitational name from Gaffert near Köslin, Brandenburg, or from a personal name formed with Middle High German <i>gate</i> ‘fellow, companion’. The surname <i>Gaffert</i> is very rare in Germany.","English: perhaps an altered form of   Gatewood  , an occupational name for a ‘goatherd’ (Middle English <i>gate-werde</i>, Old English <i>gātweard</i>) or for a ‘gate keeper’ (Middle English <i>gateward</i>, Old English <i>ʒeatweard</i>, dialect <i>gātward</i>)."]},{"name":"Gifford","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of <b>Giffard</b>, either from the Middle English personal name <i>Gifard</i>, derived from an Old French name of this form deriving from ancient Germanic <i>geb-</i> ‘give, gift’ + <i>hard-</i> ‘hardy, brave’, or perhaps sometimes a nickname from Old French <i>gif(f)ard</i> ‘chubby-cheeked, bloated’."]},{"name":"Jefferd","meanings":["English:  see  Giffard  ."]}]},{"name":"Nicholas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Nicholas Giffard was born about 1410, in Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Roger Giffard, was 44 and his mother, Isabella de Stretley, was 36. He had at least 1 daughter with Margery Dicleston. He died in 1507, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 98."},"et":{"Abt 1410–1507":"umbes 1410–1507","1405–1430":"1405–1430","1408–1469":"1408–1469","1410–1507":"1410–1507","1410–Female":"1410–Surnud","1414–1489":"1414–1489","1440–1507":"1440–1507","1367–1409":"1367–1409","1375–1415":"1375–1415","1440":"1440","1415":"1415","1414":"1414","1469":"1469","1489":"1489","Abt 1410":"umbes 1410","1367":"1367","1410":"1410","1375":"1375","1430":"1430","1407   3rd wife":"märts 1407","1409":"1409","1507":"1507","1408":"1408","1405":"1405","Bradwell, Gloucestershire, England":"Bradwell-on-Sea, Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Of, Bradwell, Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Twyford, Buckinghamshire, England":"Twyford, Buckinghamshire, England","Twyford, Buckinghamshire, England.":"Twyford, Buckinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1410–1507":"noin 1410–1507","1405–1430":"1405–1430","1408–1469":"1408–1469","1410–1507":"1410–1507","1410–Female":"1410–Kuollut","1414–1489":"1414–1489","1440–1507":"1440–1507","1367–1409":"1367–1409","1375–1415":"1375–1415","1440":"1440","1415":"1415","1414":"1414","1469":"1469","1489":"1489","Abt 1410":"noin 1410","1367":"1367","1410":"1410","1375":"1375","1430":"1430","1407   3rd wife":"maaliskuu 1407","1409":"1409","1507":"1507","1408":"1408","1405":"1405","Bradwell, Gloucestershire, England":"Bradwell-on-Sea, Essex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Of, Bradwell, Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Twyford, Buckinghamshire, England":"Twyford, Buckinghamshire, England","Twyford, Buckinghamshire, England.":"Twyford, Buckingha